---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="The Number Garden"
  description="Joyful mathematics for curious minds. The Number Garden is a warm, inquiry-driven math studio rooted in play, wonder, and deep thinking."
>
  <section class="hero">
    <div class="hero-copy">
      <p class="eyebrow">Founding families</p>
      <h1>Joyful mathematics for curious minds in Portland.</h1>
      <p class="lede">
        The Number Garden is a warm, inquiry-driven math studio for families
        who want mathematics to feel alive: playful, rigorous, beautiful, and
        full of genuine discovery. We are beginning with a small founding group
        of families in Portland.
      </p>
      <div class="actions">
        <a class="button button-primary" href="/contact/">
          Ask about fit
        </a>
        <a class="button button-secondary" href="/offerings/">
          See offerings
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>

    <aside class="hero-card" aria-label="What grows at The Number Garden">
      <p class="card-label">What grows here</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Early family math rooted in play, pattern, and wonder</li>
        <li>Rich problems worth lingering over</li>
        <li>Challenge without hurry or coercion</li>
        <li>Support for confidence, fluency, and deep thinking</li>
      </ul>
    </aside>
  </section>

  <section class="panel panel-light">
    <div class="section-heading">
      <p class="eyebrow">Who This Is For</p>
      <h2>One mathematical culture, several ways in.</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="supporting-copy">
      The Number Garden is meant to serve families with different starting
      points, without sorting children into narrow labels. The aim is one rich
      mathematical environment with lower floors, higher ceilings, and
      thoughtful entry points.
    </p>
    <div class="card-grid" aria-label="Who The Number Garden is for">
      <article class="topic-card">
        <h3>Early family math</h3>
        <p>
          For families who want young children to grow up with mathematics as
          part of home life: playful, curious, social, and full of wonder.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="topic-card">
        <h3>Deeper challenge</h3>
        <p>
          For students who are ready for richer problems, deeper challenge, and
          more real mathematical thinking than school usually offers.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="topic-card">
        <h3>Rebuilding confidence</h3>
        <p>
          For students who need steadier support, stronger foundations, and a
          warmer path back into mathematical confidence and fluency.
        </p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="panel panel-accent">
    <div class="section-heading">
      <p class="eyebrow">The Approach</p>
      <h2>A garden is not built by force.</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="supporting-copy">
      We do not believe deep learning comes from coercion, compliance, or
      forced performance. We believe it emerges when children are invited into
      an environment rich enough, beautiful enough, and alive enough that they
      lose themselves in joyful problem solving.
    </p>
    <p class="supporting-copy">
      Here, mathematics is built around play, patterns, conjectures,
      explanation, and proof. The aim is not faster worksheet completion. It is
      a more alive relationship to mathematical thinking.
    </p>
    <div class="inline-links">
      <a class="card-link" href="/about/">About the approach</a>
      <a class="card-link" href="/founder/">Meet the founder</a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="panel panel-light">
    <div class="section-heading">
      <p class="eyebrow">Pedagogy in Action</p>
      <h2>What does this look like in practice?</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="supporting-copy">
      Philosophy matters, but a mathematical culture should also be something
      you can see and feel. One of my favorite examples is Diffy Squares: a
      deceptively simple problem that invites noticing, conjecturing, testing,
      and delight.
    </p>
    <p class="supporting-copy">
      It is the kind of rich mathematical gem that can meet learners at many
      levels while still opening into real wonder.
    </p>
    <div class="inline-links">
      <a class="card-link" href="/about/#pedagogy-in-action">
        See how it fits the philosophy
      </a>
      <a class="card-link" href="/about/diffy-squares/">
        Try Diffy Squares
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="panel panel-light">
    <div class="section-heading">
      <p class="eyebrow">What Happens Next</p>
      <h2>A simple first step.</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="supporting-copy">
      If this feels like it might be a fit, start with the interest form. Share
      a little about your family, which child or children you have in mind, and
      what kind of support or challenge you are looking for.
    </p>
    <div class="card-grid" aria-label="What happens next">
      <article class="topic-card">
        <h3>1. Reach out</h3>
        <p>Fill out the short family interest form on the contact page.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="topic-card">
        <h3>2. Hear back</h3>
        <p>I follow up personally by email about fit, timing, and next steps.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="topic-card">
        <h3>3. Begin well</h3>
        <p>
          If it seems promising, we can talk further and find the right way to
          enter the studio.
        </p>
      </article>
    </div>
    <div class="inline-links">
      <a class="card-link" href="/contact/">Start with the interest form</a>
      <a class="card-link" href="/offerings/">Explore offerings</a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="panel panel-light contact-panel">
    <div class="section-heading">
      <p class="eyebrow">A Real Place</p>
      <h2>A real home in Portland.</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="contact-copy">
      The first Number Garden space will live in Portland&apos;s Hollywood
      neighborhood, at 4152 NE Sandy Blvd. What began as a philosophy is now
      taking shape in a real place, with room for mathematical play,
      conversation, and discovery.
    </p>
    <div class="actions">
      <a class="contact-link" href="/contact/">
        Get in touch
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
